The goals of BME 460, Design for People with Disabilities were:

To provide practical engineering experience to develop a system to solve an identified need.&middot;

To provide a personally rewarding experience to each student, which is highly motivating for their academic and career success.&middot;

To assist individuals with disabilities become more independent by providing custom assistive technology devices that address their specific needs.&middot;

To facilitate learning about the daily lives of individuals with disability, as well as the daily lives of the family members, therapists, and teachers who are in close contact with them.&middot;

To provide an opportunity for public service. BME 460 is a recognized Service Learning class.

This project was an interdisciplinary collaboration between students and faculty in biomedical engineering, practicing professionals in occupational and physical therapy, educators, people with disability, and those that support them. The students worked closely with the stakeholders to ensure that their projects met the needs of the clients. This interaction benefited all involved as they learned from each other. During the funding period, the Design for People with Disabilities class was one of the most requested and popular of the BME design electives available at Duke University.

Over the past 6 years, with support from the NSF, a total of 61 custom assistive devices were created by over 200 senior BME students for people with disabilities in the Durham, NC community. We partnered with more than 20 agencies that work with or serve people with disabilities including Goodwill of Central NC, the Durham, Wake, and Orange Public school systems, Orange Enterprises, Durham Exchange Club Industries, Reality Ministries, Extraordinary Ventures, and the Duke University Health system. Outcomes of the work included over 25 student publications, over 25 submissions to national and international student design competitions, and 6 student design competitions or winning submissions. Projects summaries are posted to the BME460 class website: http://sites.duke.edu/atdesign/

